<body>

<!-- HEADER -->
<div class="header">
  <div>
    <div class="tag">Course Project Proposal · End-to-End ML Application</div>
    <h1>Personalized News Headline Generation with <em>Cold-Start</em> Style Vectors</h1>
  </div>
  <div class="meta-block">
    <strong>Domain</strong> Media & NLP
    <strong>Timeline</strong> 8 Weeks
    <strong>Stack</strong> Full-Stack · CI/CD · Deployed
    <strong>Dataset</strong> Public + Scraped
  </div>
</div>

<!-- BODY -->
<div class="body">

  <!-- PROBLEM -->
  <div class="section">
    <div class="section-label">01 — Problem Statement</div>
    <h2>Every journalist writes differently. AI doesn't know that.</h2>
    <p>When an AI generates a news headline, it produces the same generic output regardless of who wrote the article. A journalist at the New York Times writes differently than one at BuzzFeed — different vocabulary, structure, tone, and rhythm. Existing headline generation models ignore this entirely.</p>
    <p>There is a research method called <strong>StyleVector</strong> (Zhang et al., 2025) that can learn a journalist's writing style and use it to guide AI generation. However, it has a critical flaw: it only works well when the journalist has written <strong>50 or more articles</strong>. For newer or less prolific writers, the method breaks down.</p>
    <p>This project directly solves that gap.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- NOVEL CONTRIBUTION -->
  <div class="section">
    <div class="section-label">02 — Novel Contribution</div>
    <h2>The Cold-Start Problem in Style Learning</h2>

    <div class="contribution-box">
      <div class="label">Core Research Question</div>
      <p>When a journalist has written only 5–15 articles, can we still generate headlines that match their writing style — by borrowing from stylistically similar, more experienced writers?</p>
    </div>

    <p>The proposed solution is <strong>Cold-Start Style Vector Initialization</strong>. Instead of computing a noisy, unreliable style fingerprint from too little data, the system identifies which cluster of writers the new journalist most resembles, then blends their sparse data with the style patterns of that cluster.</p>

    <div class="two-col">
      <div class="col-card">
        <div class="card-title">What the existing paper does</div>
        <ul>
          <li>Learns a "style vector" per author from their writing history</li>
          <li>Uses that vector to steer AI generation at inference time</li>
          <li>Requires 50–287 articles per author to work reliably</li>
          <li>Completely untested on authors with sparse history</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="col-card">
        <div class="card-title">What this project adds</div>
        <ul>
          <li>Groups established writers into style clusters</li>
          <li>For a new writer, finds their nearest style cluster</li>
          <li>Blends sparse personal data with cluster knowledge</li>
          <li>Demonstrates measurable improvement over existing method</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- PIPELINE -->
  <div class="section">
    <div class="section-label">03 — How It Works</div>
    <h2>Four-Stage Technical Pipeline</h2>

    <div class="pipeline">
      <div class="step">
        <div class="step-num">01</div>
        <div class="step-title">Style-Agnostic Generation</div>
        <div class="step-desc">For every article in the dataset, use Gemini AI to generate a plain, generic headline — one without any personal style. This becomes the "baseline" to contrast against.</div>
        <div class="step-arrow">→</div>
      </div>
      <div class="step">
        <div class="step-num">02</div>
        <div class="step-title">Style Vector Extraction</div>
        <div class="step-desc">For each established author, compare the real headline (stylistic) against the generic one (neutral) inside the language model's internal layers. The difference becomes a style fingerprint.</div>
        <div class="step-arrow">→</div>
      </div>
      <div class="step">
        <div class="step-num">03</div>
        <div class="step-title">Cold-Start Interpolation</div>
        <div class="step-desc">Group style fingerprints into clusters. For sparse authors with few articles, blend their noisy fingerprint with the nearest cluster center to produce a stable, reliable style vector.</div>
        <div class="step-arrow">→</div>
      </div>
      <div class="step">
        <div class="step-num">04</div>
        <div class="step-title">Steered Generation</div>
        <div class="step-desc">At inference time, inject the style vector into the language model's computation. The model generates a headline that reflects the specific journalist's voice, not a generic average.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- DATASET -->
  <div class="section">
    <div class="section-label">04 — Dataset</div>
    <h2>Two Complementary Sources</h2>
    <p>The project uses publicly available data combined with targeted scraping of Indian news sources. No private or proprietary data is used.</p>

    <div style="margin-top: 8px;">
      <div class="dataset-row">
        <div class="dataset-name">All The News<br><span style="font-size:12px;color:var(--muted);font-weight:400">Kaggle · Primary</span></div>
        <div class="dataset-desc">Articles from 50+ US publications including NYT, Reuters, Guardian, NPR, and BuzzFeed. Contains individual author bylines, publication dates, full article content, and headlines. Used for main model training and evaluation.</div>
        <div class="dataset-count">~200k<span>articles</span></div>
      </div>
      <div class="dataset-row">
        <div class="dataset-name">Times of India &<br>Hindustan Times<br><span style="font-size:12px;color:var(--muted);font-weight:400">Scraped · Secondary</span></div>
        <div class="dataset-desc">Named individual journalists scraped from Indian publications. Used as an additional validation set to test whether the method generalizes across Indian journalism styles — a genuine additional finding beyond the original paper.</div>
        <div class="dataset-count">~2–3k<span>articles</span></div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p style="margin-top: 20px; font-size: 13.5px; color: var(--muted);">Authors are filtered strictly: only named individuals (no desk accounts), minimum article count thresholds enforced, and articles split chronologically into train/validation/test sets.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- EVALUATION -->
  <div class="section">
    <div class="section-label">05 — Evaluation</div>
    <h2>Four Baselines. One Clear Story.</h2>
    <p>The experiment compares four methods across two author groups: <strong>rich authors</strong> (50+ articles) and <strong>sparse authors</strong> (5–15 articles). The key finding should show that the proposed method is the only one that performs well in both groups.</p>

    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Method</th>
          <th>Personalization</th>
          <th>Rich Authors</th>
          <th>Sparse Authors</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>No Personalization (base LLM)</td>
          <td>None</td>
          <td>Weak</td>
          <td>Weak</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>RAG — Retrieval Augmented Generation</td>
          <td>Retrieves similar past articles</td>
          <td>Moderate</td>
          <td>Poor</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>StyleVector (original paper)</td>
          <td>Full style vector</td>
          <td>Strong</td>
          <td>Degrades badly</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="highlight-row">
          <td>Cold-Start StyleVector <span class="badge">Ours</span></td>
          <td>Cluster-interpolated style vector</td>
          <td>Strong</td>
          <td>Strong</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <p style="margin-top: 20px;">Metrics used: <strong>ROUGE-L</strong> (word overlap), <strong>METEOR</strong> (accounts for synonyms), and <strong>BERTScore</strong> (semantic similarity). These are the same metrics used in the original paper, ensuring direct comparability.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- APPLICATION -->
  <div class="section">
    <div class="section-label">06 — Application</div>
    <h2>Full-Stack Web Application</h2>
    <p>The project delivers a complete, deployed web application with a React frontend and Python backend, connected via a REST API.</p>

    <div class="two-col" style="margin-top: 24px;">
      <div class="col-card">
        <div class="card-title">What the app does</div>
        <ul>
          <li>Journalist pastes their article into the interface</li>
          <li>Selects their name from a dropdown (or registers as new)</li>
          <li>System detects if they are a rich or sparse author</li>
          <li>Generates a personalized headline using their style</li>
          <li>Shows side-by-side comparison: generic vs personalized</li>
          <li>Displays style cluster the author belongs to</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="col-card">
        <div class="card-title">What the results page shows</div>
        <ul>
          <li>Evaluation table across all four methods</li>
          <li>Performance chart: rich vs sparse author groups</li>
          <li>t-SNE visualization of style vector clusters</li>
          <li>Case studies from Indian and US journalism</li>
          <li>Cold-start interpolation effect at different alpha values</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- TECH STACK -->
  <div class="section">
    <div class="section-label">07 — Technology Stack</div>
    <h2>End-to-End Technical Architecture</h2>

    <div class="tech-grid">
      <div class="tech-item">
        <div class="tech-layer">Frontend</div>
        <div class="tech-name">Next.js + Tailwind</div>
        <div class="tech-desc">React-based web interface deployed on Vercel. Connects to backend via REST API calls.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="tech-item">
        <div class="tech-layer">Backend</div>
        <div class="tech-name">FastAPI (Python)</div>
        <div class="tech-desc">Serves headline generation requests. Loads pre-computed style vectors and applies cold-start interpolation at runtime.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="tech-item">
        <div class="tech-layer">Deployment</div>
        <div class="tech-name">HuggingFace Spaces</div>
        <div class="tech-desc">Backend deployed as a Docker container on HuggingFace Spaces. Free tier, publicly accessible.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="tech-item">
        <div class="tech-layer">Style-Agnostic Generation</div>
        <div class="tech-name">Gemini API</div>
        <div class="tech-desc">Google Gemini generates generic, style-free headlines used as the neutral baseline during style vector extraction.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="tech-item">
        <div class="tech-layer">Core Language Model</div>
        <div class="tech-name">LLaMA-2-7B</div>
        <div class="tech-desc">Open-source model from Meta. Style vectors are extracted from its internal layers. Run on Kaggle/Colab GPU during training — not at runtime.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="tech-item">
        <div class="tech-layer">CI/CD Pipeline</div>
        <div class="tech-name">GitHub Actions</div>
        <div class="tech-desc">Automated testing on every commit. Auto-deployment to HuggingFace Spaces when code is merged into the main branch.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- TIMELINE -->
  <div class="section">
    <div class="section-label">08 — Timeline</div>
    <h2>8-Week Execution Plan</h2>

    <div class="timeline">

      <div class="timeline-row">
