<!-- SECTION 7: DATASET CONSTRUCTION -->
<!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<div class="section">
  <h1><span class="sec-num">§7</span> Dataset Construction</h1>

  <h2>Primary Dataset: All The News (Kaggle)</h2>
  <p>The All The News dataset contains approximately 200,000 articles from 50+ US publications including the New York Times, Reuters, The Guardian, NPR, BuzzFeed, Breitbart, and Atlantic. Each article has an individual author byline, publication date, full article body, and a headline. This is the main training and evaluation corpus.</p>

  <p>Author filtering is applied strictly. An author is included only if they are a named individual (not "Staff", "AP", "Editorial Board" or similar), have at least 50 articles in the dataset, with articles spanning at least 3 calendar months, and with an average article length exceeding 200 words. After filtering, approximately 80–150 rich authors are expected to remain.</p>

  <p>For the sparse-author experiment group, authors with 5–20 articles who pass the name filter and length threshold are retained separately. Hundreds of such authors exist in the dataset.</p>

  <h2>Secondary Dataset: Indian News Scrape</h2>
  <p>The Times of India (TOI) and Hindustan Times (HT) are scraped targeting individual journalist bylines on their author profile pages. The existing collected dataset of 1,019 TOI articles is the starting point, but it requires significant remediation: 994 of those articles are missing dates, and most "authors" are shared desk accounts rather than individuals.</p>

  <p>The scraping pipeline re-collects articles with mandatory date capture, targeting only named individual journalists with at least 30 articles on their profile page. This produces approximately 20–30 Indian journalists with 30–80 articles each, totaling 2,000–3,000 articles. This corpus is used as a <em>held-out cross-cultural evaluation set</em>, not for training.</p>

  <h2>Unified Schema</h2>
  <p>Both datasets are standardized into a common schema before any processing. Every article record contains: a unique article ID, canonical author name, headline text, full article body, ISO-format date, publication name, content section, word count, and dataset source tag. Articles are split chronologically (not randomly) per author into 70% train, 15% validation, and 15% test to respect the temporal nature of style learning.</p>
</div>


<!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<!-- SECTION 8: EVALUATION FRAMEWORK -->
<!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<div class="section">
  <h1><span class="sec-num">§8</span> Evaluation Framework</h1>

  <h2>Primary Metrics</h2>
  <p>The same metrics as the StyleVector paper are used to ensure direct comparability:</p>
  <ul class="report-list">
    <li><strong>ROUGE-L:</strong> Longest common subsequence overlap between the generated headline and the reference. Measures lexical similarity.</li>
    <li><strong>METEOR:</strong> Extends ROUGE by considering synonyms, stemming, and word order. More robust for natural language variation.</li>
    <li><strong>BERTScore:</strong> Computes semantic similarity using BERT embeddings. Captures meaning even when exact wording differs.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Additional Metric (Novel)</h2>
  <p><strong>Style Attribution Accuracy:</strong> A binary classification experiment is run where a logistic regression classifier is trained on rich-author style vectors and tested on generated headlines. The question posed is: <em>does the generated headline activate representations in the model that are consistent with the target author's style?</em> Higher accuracy indicates the generated headline is stylistically recognized as belonging to the target author. This metric is not in the original paper.</p>

  <h2>Ablation Studies</h2>
  <p>The following ablations are reported to fully characterize the cold-start method:</p>
  <ul class="report-list">
    <li>Effect of α on sparse author performance (α sweep from 0.2 to 0.8)</li>
    <li>Effect of number of clusters K on interpolation quality (K sweep from 5 to 20)</li>
    <li>Effect of sparse author history size: 5 vs 10 vs 15 vs 20 articles</li>
    <li>Cross-cultural evaluation: rich-author clusters (US) applied to sparse Indian authors</li>
  </ul>
</div>


